Problem definition¶

This project aims to develop a robust regression model for predicting aircraft Take-Off Weight (TOW), a critical parameter in aviation operations that directly impacts fuel consumption, flight planning, and operational efficiency.

Analysis datasets

  • Training Dataset (training.csv): Historical flight data from Ryanair operations spanning October 1-15, 2016, containing comprehensive flight parameters and corresponding Take-Off Weight measurements for model development and training.
  • Validation Dataset (validation.csv): A separate dataset with identical feature structure but without Take-Off Weight values, serving as the prediction target for model validation and performance assessment.

Performance criteria

Model performance is evaluated using Root Mean Square Error (RMSE), which provides:

  • Interpretable error metrics in the same units as the target variable
  • Appropriate penalty for larger prediction errors
  • Industry-standard benchmark for regression model assessment

3. Process data frame features¶

This step performs preprocessing and feature engineering to prepare the dataset for modeling:

  • Data Type Conversion: Convert relevant columns (especially dates and numerics) to appropriate types for analysis.
  • Missing Value Handle:
    • Baggage counts - estimates are computed using an average of 0.7 bags per passenger.
    • Baggage weights - estimates assume 15 kg per bag.
  • New Feature Engineer: Calculate several derived metrics:
    • FuelPerPassenger – average fuel consumption (kg) per passenger.
    • BagLoadFactor – average number of bags per passenger.
    • Month – extracted from the flight's departure date.
    • DayOfWeek – numeric representation of the weekday (0 = Monday, 6 = Sunday).
    • IsWeekend – binary indicator for weekend flights (Saturday or Sunday).
    • EstimatedDistance – estimated distance of the route in kilometers; based on known routes or average distance if unknown.

This preprocessing ensures consistency, fills data gaps intelligently, and enriches the dataset with meaningful features for model training and evaluation.

In [143]:
def _process_dataframe_features(df, is_training=True):
        """Helper method to process features for both training and prediction data"""
        
        if 'DepartureDate' in df.columns:
            df['DepartureDate'] = pd.to_datetime(df['DepartureDate'], format='%d/%m/%Y')
        
        # Convert numeric columns and handle missing values
        numeric_columns = ['ActualTotalFuel', 'FLownPassengers', 'FlightBagsWeight', 'BagsCount', 'ActualFlightTime']
        if is_training:
            numeric_columns.append('ActualTOW')
        
        for col in numeric_columns:
            if col in df.columns:
                df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors='coerce')
        
        # Handle missing bag data
        missing_bags = df['BagsCount'].isnull()
        missing_bag_weight = df['FlightBagsWeight'].isnull()
        
        # Estimate missing bag counts (0.7 bags per passenger average)
        df.loc[missing_bags, 'BagsCount'] = (df.loc[missing_bags, 'FLownPassengers'] * 0.7).round()
        
        # Estimate missing bag weights (15kg per bag average)
        df.loc[missing_bag_weight, 'FlightBagsWeight'] = df.loc[missing_bag_weight, 'BagsCount'] * 15
                
        # Fuel efficiency metrics
        df['FuelPerPassenger'] = df['ActualTotalFuel'] / df['FLownPassengers']
        
        # Load factors
        df['BagLoadFactor'] = df['BagsCount'] / df['FLownPassengers']
        
        # Temporal features
        if 'DepartureDate' in df.columns:
            df['Month'] = df['DepartureDate'].dt.month
            df['DayOfWeek'] = df['DepartureDate'].dt.dayofweek
            df['IsWeekend'] = (df['DayOfWeek'] >= 5).astype(int)
        
        route_distances = {
            'KUN-RHO': 2084,  # Kaunas to Rhodes
            'STN-KRK': 1378,  # London Stansted to Krakow
            'KRK-STN': 1378,  # Krakow to London Stansted
            'STN-LCJ': 1313,  # London Stansted to Lodz
            'LBA-TSF': 1346,  # Leeds Bradford to Treviso
            'BCN-CGN': 1132,  # Barcelona to Cologne
            'CGN-BCN': 1132,  # Cologne to Barcelona
            'AGP-BLL': 2354,  # Malaga to Billund
            'NYO-AGP': 2987,  # Stockholm Skavsta to Malaga
            'AGP-SXF': 2112,  # Malaga to Berlin Schönefeld
            'PDL-LIS': 1452,  # Ponta Delgada to Lisbon
            'STN-CIA': 1434,  # London Stansted to Rome Ciampino
            'BRU-PMI': 1329,  # Brussels to Palma de Mallorca
            'BRU-BCN': 1065,  # Brussels to Barcelona
            'MRS-BES': 624,   # Marseille to Brest
            'BES-MRS': 624,   # Brest to Marseille
            'MRS-STN': 1004,  # Marseille to London Stansted
            'STN-MRS': 1004,  # London Stansted to Marseille
            'STN-REU': 1213,  # London Stansted to Reus
            'REU-STN': 1213,  # Reus to London Stansted
            'STN-DUB': 463,   # London Stansted to Dublin
            'DUB-STN': 463,   # Dublin to London Stansted
            'STN-NYO': 1420,  # London Stansted to Stockholm Skavsta
            'GDN-NYO': 789    # Gdansk to Stockholm Skavsta
        }
        mean_distance = sum(route_distances.values()) / len(route_distances)
        df['EstimatedDistance'] = df['Route'].map(route_distances).fillna(mean_distance)
            
        return df
    
df = _process_dataframe_features(df)

5. Prepare features for modeling¶

Following code section prepares the dataset for machine learning by implementing following feature engineering pipeline:

Feature Selection: Model uses 13 input features including operational metrics (FlownPassengers, ActualTotalFuel, FlightBagsWeight, BagsCount), temporal variables (ActualFlightTime, EstimatedDistance), operational factors (FuelPerPassenger, BagLoadFactor), and categorical time dimensions (Month, DayOfWeek, IsWeekend).

Categorical Encoding: Departure and arrival airports are transformed from categorical text data (e.g., "MAN", "SXF", "LGW") into numerical representations using Label Encoding, creating DepartureAirport_encoded and ArrivalAirport_encoded features that capture airport-specific patterns affecting aircraft weight.

Data Cleaning: The pipeline handles missing values by removing rows where the target variable (ActualTOW) is null, then applies median imputation for missing feature values to maintain dataset integrity without losing valuable samples.

Target Preparation: ActualTOW serves as the dependent variable, with the cleaned dataset containing 29,298 samples ready for model training. The preprocessing ensures all 13 features are numerical and complete, enabling the Random Forest algorithm to learn complex relationships between flight characteristics and take-off weight.

In [153]:
def prepare_features_for_modeling():
    """Prepare features for machine learning models"""
    
    # Select features for modeling
    feature_columns = [
        'FLownPassengers', 'ActualTotalFuel', 'FlightBagsWeight', 'BagsCount',
        'ActualFlightTime', 'EstimatedDistance', 'FuelPerPassenger', 
        'BagLoadFactor', 'Month', 'DayOfWeek', 'IsWeekend'
    ]
    
    # Encode categorical variables if needed
    le_airport = LabelEncoder()
    df['DepartureAirport_encoded'] = le_airport.fit_transform(df['DepartureAirport'])
    df['ArrivalAirport_encoded'] = le_airport.fit_transform(df['ArrivalAirport'])
    
    feature_columns.extend(['DepartureAirport_encoded', 'ArrivalAirport_encoded'])
    
    # Remove rows with missing target variable
    clean_df = df.dropna(subset=['ActualTOW'])
    
    X = clean_df[feature_columns].fillna(clean_df[feature_columns].median())
    y = clean_df['ActualTOW']
    
    print(f"Features selected: {len(feature_columns)}")
    print(f"Samples for modeling: {len(X)}")
    
    return X, y, feature_columns

6.1. Regression Models description¶

Linear Regression - establishes a direct linear relationship between input features and the target variable. It assumes that the relationship can be represented as a straight line through the data points, making it the simplest and most interpretable model in the collection. This baseline model provides coefficients that directly show how each feature influences the prediction.

Ridge Regression - extends linear regression by adding L2 regularization with an alpha parameter of 1.0. The regularization term penalizes large coefficients, which helps prevent overfitting and handles multicollinearity between features. This technique shrinks coefficient values toward zero but never eliminates them completely, making the model more stable when dealing with correlated predictors.

Lasso Regression - incorporates L1 regularization with alpha set to 1.0, which not only penalizes large coefficients but can drive some coefficients to exactly zero. This feature selection capability makes Lasso particularly useful for identifying the most important predictors while automatically removing less relevant features from the model. The resulting model is often more interpretable due to its sparse nature.

Random Forest - combines 100 decision trees (n_estimators=100) trained on different bootstrap samples of the data. Each tree uses a random subset of features at each split, reducing overfitting while maintaining predictive power. The final prediction is the average of all individual tree predictions, making it robust to outliers and capable of capturing complex non-linear relationships and feature interactions.

Gradient Boosting - builds an ensemble of 100 weak learners (typically shallow decision trees) in a sequential manner. Each new tree is trained to correct the errors made by the previous trees, gradually improving the overall prediction accuracy. This iterative approach often achieves high performance but requires careful tuning to avoid overfitting, especially with the fixed random state ensuring reproducible results.

In [158]:
results = {}

for name, model in models_to_test.items():
    print(f"\nTraining {name}...")
    
    # Use scaled data for linear models, original for tree-based
    if 'Regression' in name and 'Random' not in name and 'Gradient' not in name:
        model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)
        y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train_scaled)
    else:
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
        y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    
    # Calculate metrics
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
    mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_test, y_pred) * 100
    
    # Training metrics (to check overfitting)
    train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
    train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
    
    results[name] = {
        'model': model,
        'MAE': mae,
        'RMSE': rmse,
        'R²': r2,
        'MAPE': mape,
        'Train_MAE': train_mae,
        'Train_R²': train_r2,
        'predictions': y_pred,
        'actual': y_test
    }
    
    print('Done!')

6.2. Model Performance Parameters description¶

Test MAE (Mean Absolute Error) - measures the average magnitude of prediction errors in kilograms, representing how far off the predictions are from actual TOW values on average. Lower values indicate better performance. Random Forest achieves the best MAE of 664.6 kg, meaning its predictions are typically within about 665 kg of the true takeoff weight, while the linear models show higher errors around 770 kg.

Test RMSE (Root Mean Square Error) - penalizes larger errors more heavily than MAE by squaring the differences before averaging and taking the square root. This metric is more sensitive to outliers and large prediction errors. Random Forest again performs best with 907.7 kg RMSE, suggesting it handles extreme predictions better than other models. The consistently higher RMSE compared to MAE across all models indicates the presence of some larger prediction errors.

Test MAPE (Mean Absolute Percentage Error) - expresses prediction errors as percentages of the actual values, making it easier to interpret across different scales. Random Forest achieves 1.02% MAPE, meaning its predictions are typically within about 1% of the true TOW values. The linear models show slightly higher percentage errors around 1.19%, indicating Random Forest provides more consistent relative accuracy.

Test R² (R-squared) - represents the proportion of variance in TOW that the model explains, ranging from 0 to 1 where higher values indicate better fit. Random Forest explains 92.5% of the variance, while linear models explain about 88.5%. This metric shows how well the model captures the underlying patterns in the data compared to simply predicting the mean value.

Train R² - shows how well each model fits the training data. The large gap between Random Forest's training R² (0.989) and test R² (0.925) indicates overfitting, where the model memorizes training patterns that don't generalize well. Linear models show minimal difference between training and test scores, suggesting they capture more generalizable patterns.

Overfitting Assessment - qualitative measure compares training and test performance to identify models that memorize rather than learn generalizable patterns. Random Forest shows "High" overfitting due to the significant gap between its training and test R² scores. Linear models demonstrate "Low" overfitting with nearly identical training and test performance, while Gradient Boosting falls in between with "Moderate" overfitting.

Results¶

Random Forest regression model demonstrates superior predictive performance for aircraft take-off weight estimation, significantly outperforming traditional linear approaches:

Model Performance Comparison: Random Forest achieves the lowest prediction errors with MAE of 664.6 kg and RMSE of 907.7, substantially outperforming Linear Regression variants (MAE ~770 kg, RMSE ~1123-1125). It is 15% improvement in accuracy over conventional methods demonstrates the value of ensemble techniques for capturing complex weight relationships in dataset.

Prediction Quality Assessment: The model exhibits excellent accuracy characteristics:

  • Unbiased Predictions: Residuals follow a normal distribution centered at -4.1 kg, indicating minimal systematic error
  • Consistent Performance: Residuals remain within ±2,000 kg for most predictions, with tight clustering around the perfect prediction line
  • Full Range Accuracy: Model maintains prediction quality across the entire operational spectrum from 47,000 kg to 78,000 kg

Feature Importance Insights: The model correctly identifies ActualTotalFuel (63.0% importance) as the primary TOW determinant, followed by FlownPassengers (25.7% importance). This feature ranking aligns with aviation physics, where fuel load and passenger count represent the major variable weight components affecting take-off weight.
